## 4. **Bubble Sort (Java)**

```java
public class BubbleSort {

    public static void bubbleSort(int[] arr) {
        int n = arr.length;

        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            boolean swapped = false;

            for (int j = 0; j < n - i - 1; j++) {
                if (arr[j] > arr[j + 1]) {
                    // Swap
                    int temp = arr[j];
                    arr[j] = arr[j + 1];
                    arr[j + 1] = temp;
                    swapped = true;
                }
            }

            if (!swapped) break;
        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int[] arr = {64, 34, 25, 12, 22, 11, 90};

        System.out.println("Original array: " + Arrays.toString(arr));
        bubbleSort(arr);
        System.out.println("Sorted array: " + Arrays.toString(arr));
    }
}
```

## 5. **Bubble Sort (C++)**

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>
using namespace std;

void bubbleSort(vector<int>& arr) {
    int n = arr.size();

    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        bool swapped = false;

        for (int j = 0; j < n - i - 1; j++) {
            if (arr[j] > arr[j + 1]) {
                swap(arr[j], arr[j + 1]);
                swapped = true;
            }
        }

        if (!swapped) break;
    }
}

int main() {
    vector<int> arr = {64, 34, 25, 12, 22, 11, 90};

    cout << "Original: ";
    for (int x : arr) cout << x << " ";

    bubbleSort(arr);

    cout << "\nSorted: ";
    for (int x : arr) cout << x << " ";

    return 0;
}
```

## 6. **Generic Bubble Sort with Comparator (Python)**

```python
def bubble_sort_generic(arr, reverse=False):
    """
    Bubble sort with custom sorting order
    """
    n = len(arr)

    for i in range(n):
        for j in range(0, n - i - 1):
            # Ascending order
            if not reverse and arr[j] > arr[j + 1]:
                arr[j], arr[j + 1] = arr[j + 1], arr[j]
            # Descending order
            elif reverse and arr[j] < arr[j + 1]:
                arr[j], arr[j + 1] = arr[j + 1], arr[j]

    return arr


# Test
arr1 = [5, 2, 8, 1, 9]
print("Ascending:", bubble_sort_generic(arr1))
print("Descending:", bubble_sort_generic(arr1.copy(), reverse=True))
```

## **Algorithm Analysis**

| Aspect | Value |
|--------|-------|
| **Time Complexity (Best)** | O(n) - Already sorted |
| **Time Complexity (Average)** | O(n²) |
| **Time Complexity (Worst)** | O(n²) - Reverse sorted |
| **Space Complexity** | O(1) - In-place |
| **Stable?** | Yes |
| **Adaptive?** | Yes (with optimization) |

## **Key Points**

✅ Simple to understand and implement  
✅ In-place sorting (minimal extra space)  
✅ Stable sort  
✅ Good for small datasets  
❌ Poor performance on large datasets  
❌ Many unnecessary comparisons

Choose the **optimized version** for better performance!

